text: I love how trailers nowadays always show too much. I feel like I don't need to see this now. Starts off with a large crew, then an accident happens, then it looks like a big storm comes up and obviously a few people die from falling and people letting ropes slip. That one guy freezes to death then the trailer ends on a sunny day with just TWO people bracing each other slowly walking down? Come fucking on. High school film study kids could make a better and less revealing trailer than this. Also, guaranteed one of those two is either Josh Brolin or the guy from Planet of the Apes. Such disappointment.  The whole trailer should have ended with either them looking up at this big and daunting mountain or once they reached the top, it pans over to that huge storm then cuts out. That would have been much better than showing me everything that happens.

It is suicide if you plan to go there. The costs are big (approx. $200,000 U.S.) and to die there is obviously not an ideal place to be. You become a 'sign post' to the next waive of climbers who dare to climb this mountain.

text: The Eight-thousanders of Himalaya are the most inhospitable places on this Earth. Now, I`m pretty sure that every part of your skin has to be covered at all times by several layers at this altitude. If you don`t want necrosis that is.¬† It`s almost as bad as in space itself, so your outfit must be something close to a spacesuit. You can`t cross the Khumbu Icefall looking like you`re on a ski trip at a few thousand feet. Aaaanyway, it`s nothing new that blockbusters aren`t successful because of their accuracy, so I`m not really complaining. Showing the faces of the movie stars are after all the most important thing here... Still; it looks like fun. I`ll watch it when it premieres.

text: The very first shot isn't a shot of Everest or CG composite shot of the correct mountain either -you'd think they'd get that right .....  It takes until :19 and the fourth shot before they actually get a real shot of Everest.  Still looks awesome though and it's good that this version might do Krakauer's book some justice.  Curious to see how they treat Sally Pittman, how they address the Outfitter competition and how they address the hubris which ultimately caused the disaster.  Also, it is a common misconception that the climbers and camps didn't expect that storm -they knew it was coming for a week -they just hoped it was not intense enough to allow them to descend from high camp the next day -as neither group wanted to be the ones to turn around.

text: Watched it just now in 3D which adds so much to the movie, stunning pictures! I read a few comments from people complaining the movie was too slow - personally I think it is what made the movie so good, the development of the characters you really feel some empathy later with. Ok, climbing the Mount Everest is something potentially very dangerous and they were quite aware of it, that is unquestionable and then simply bad things happened which were out of their control.   I am really glad it was not one of those action-stuffed movies but took its time to introduce the people - movie had my constant attention and that is rare. One of those stories you go later online and read more about it, always appreciated!

text: This was a great movie!  They sell you the seat, but all you need is the edge!  I had just finished reading Blind Descent (great book too!) by Brian Dickinson and heard this movie was coming out.  I was excited to see some of the images I had read about in the book brought to life and wasn't disappointed!  I saw this movie in 3D and it was great, but I would only give it 4 out of 5 stars because they neglected to apply a timeline.  The movie makes it seem like the Everest summit only took a couple days.  If they had simply applied 'day 45' etc., it would have increased the impact of what the climbers were actually experiencing.  Overall a great movie and I highly recommend!

text: As a guy who spends a lot of time backpacking, which is a different animal than mountaineering, it's been an interesting year. 2 books I really enjoyed, A Walk in the Woods and Into Thin Air were made in to movies. "Wild," which I also read, was pretty much a therapy session for women.  "A Walk in the Woods" which is a GREAT book was a joke of a movie. "Wild" was just silly.  But I saw Everest last night. While it's not the book because it doesn't come from the author's perspective, I found it absolutely riveting and the closest thing to capturing the power of nature and the suffering that can come from being in it. It blew my mind that the theater was about 2/3 empty. It seemed to have just enough "Hollywood" drama to hook the typical audience member but enough specifics for those looking for realism.  HIGHLY recommend this film.  At the very least, I sure hope that it puts an end to the bullshit people spew from their couches whenever there's a tragedy about how "anyone can climb Everest" and that Sherpas "drag people up the mountain." That really pisses me off because it's nothing but pure garbage. 98% of people couldn't make it to base camp. And that's a fact.
